    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT90-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">varaivu nīṭṭittavaḻi āṟṟāḷākiya talaimakaṭkut talaimakaṉ ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi kūṟiyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken by the confidante, while HE was behind the hedge, to HER who didn't have the strength [anymore] when [he] delayed marriage.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT90">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                eṟṟō vāḻi tōḻi muṟṟupu</l>
<l>                kaṟivaḷa raṭukkat tiraviṉ muḻaṅkiya</l>
<l>                maṅkuṉ māmaḻai vīḻnteṉap poṅkumayirk</l>
<l>                kalaitoṭa viḻukkiya pūnāṟu palavukkaṉi</l>
<l>                varaiyiḻi yaruvi yuṇṭuṟait tarūuṅ</l>
<l>                kuṉṟa nāṭaṉ kēṇmai</l>
<l>                meṉṟōḷ cāyttuñ cālpiṉ ṟaṉṟē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>Why is it, oh friend?</l>
                <l>
                    <choice>
                        <seg>It is something noble, isn't it,</seg>
                        <seg>It is not noble,</seg>
                    </choice>
                </l>
                <l rend="indent3">even when bending<note place="foot">Actually <term xml:lang="ta">cāyttum</term>, transitive of <term xml:lang="ta">cāytal</term>, intr. "to bend" (DEDR 2456), is not satisfactory. We could either think of an adhoc transitive formation to <term xml:lang="ta">cāytal</term>, "to be emaciated" (DEDR 2453), or we could think of emending into <term xml:lang="ta">cāyntum</term>.</note> [my] soft shoulders,</l>
                <l>the intimacy with the man from the hills,</l>
                <l rend="indent">where the waterfall plunging from the mountain</l>
                <l rend="indent">brings<note place="foot">For the gift of the waters cf. KT 109.2: <term xml:lang="ta">ikutirai tarūun tuṟaivaṉ</term>.</note> to the collyrium ghat<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uṇ tuṟai</term> is ambiguous and may on the one hand refer to the collyrium-dark colour of the water, on the other hand to its status as drinking water reservoir. In KT 399.1 <term xml:lang="ta">uṇ kēṇi</term> "drinking water well" precedes the <term xml:lang="ta">uṇtuṟai</term>. Perhaps the double employment of <term xml:lang="ta">uṇ</term> in one phrase points to the fact that both meanings could be actualised.</note> the ripe fruit of the jackfruit tree</l>
                <l rend="indent">fragrant with flowers that had slipped off</l>
                <l rend="indent">at the touch of the male monkey with bushy(?)<note place="foot">poṅku, literally "to foam", but with hair "to become erect", seems to be too special a formulation to be just taken as an attribute denoting the mass of hair, as is understood by Cām. TVG renders it with "bushy".</note> hair,</l>
                <l rend="indent">because<note place="foot">Is the <term xml:lang="ta">vīḻnteṉa</term> clause to be connected with <term xml:lang="ta">varai iḻi yaruvi</term>?</note> great rains had fallen from the cloud</l>
                <l rend="indent">that thundered at night near the mountain side</l>
                <l rend="indent4">grown with ripe pepper.</l>
                </lg>
        </div>
